President Biden has announced his intent to appoint several individuals to key roles in the Coordinating Council on Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention and the President's Advisory Committee on the Arts. For the Coordinating Council, Amiyah Davis, an advocate and activist for youth in the juvenile justice system, will serve as a member. Michael Anthony Mendoza, the Director of Advocacy at the Anti-Recidivism Coalition, and Liz Simons, Chair of the Board of the Heising-Simons Foundation, will also serve as members. For the President's Advisory Committee on the Arts, Liz Beretta-Perik, a supporter of healthcare, children, women, and the arts, will serve as a member. Farah Cook, a partner at Kilpatrick Townsend & Stockton LLP, Catherine Hurst Gledhill, a member of various boards and committees supporting education and healthcare, Teena Hostovich, Vice Chair of Lockton Insurance Brokers, Shahid Ahmed Khan, a community leader and political advisor, and Noah Bryson Mamet, former U.S. Ambassador to Argentina, will also serve as members. Additionally, Joan Sestak, Director of Community and Governmental Relations for the University of Illinois Springfield, will serve as a member of the Route 66 Centennial Commission.